  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.7865" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>London<lb/> 64, St. Geoge’s Square,<lb/> S. W. 7/4/82 </dateline>
        <opener>Dear Sir, </opener>
        <p>I am in receipt of your letter of March 21, and am glad to make your acquaintance: I read German with ease, but I prefer writing to my friends in English.</p>

        <p>In my list of Languages of Africa (now ready exceding 300) I came upon no one, which is made up in the manner so well known as Pidgeon-English<note
            n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Der erste Beleg für diesen Begriff stammt vom Jahr 1826 (<hi
              rend="unknown" rendition="#none">pigeon</hi>); seit 1859 <hi rend="unknown"
              rendition="#none">pidgeon</hi>, seit 1876 <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.47">
              <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">pidgin</hi>
            </ref>. Die Etymologie ist unklar.</note> - No doubt the Kru-boys,<note n="2" place="foot"
            type="editorial">Meist „Crewboys“, afrikanische Seeleute, die ursprünglich aus Liberia kamen und meist auf Frachtschiffen arbeiteten.</note> and <pb
            facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/> other races on the West Coast who conduct business with the English and French, do use broken French and English, but that is not what you require.</p>

        <p>In the West Indies, the Bible is translated in a compound of English and Dutch as used by the Negroes: I tried to get a copy for you at the Bible house: they only have one copy as a specimen. <pb
            facs="#IMG.3" n="3"/> On the confines of China and Russia I find in Schuyler’s book on Russia<note n="3"
            place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.7367">Eugene Schuyler, <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Turkistan, notes of a journey in Russian Turkistan, Khokand, Bukhara, and Kuldja ; with 3 maps and numerous illustrations</hi> ; in 2 volumes, London: Sampson Low, Marston, Searle &amp;amp; Rivington, 1876.</ref>
            </bibl>
          </note> that the Chinese have made a <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.934">
Pidgeon-Russian</ref>.<note n="4" place="foot" type="editorial">Nicht identifiziert.</note>
        </p>

        <p>I am most interested in your labours: should you like to publish a paper in the Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society<note
            n="5" place="foot" type="editorial">Die 
Royal Asiatic Society ist eine britische Gelehrtengesellschaft. Sie wurde 1823 auf Initiative des Orientalisten <persName>
Henry Thomas Colebrooke</persName> in London gegründet, wo sie bis heute ihren Sitz hat, und erhielt 1824 von König Georg IV. die Royal Charter (wikipedia).</note>– and will send it to me in German, I will translate it: this will at once draw attention to the subject.</p>
        <pb facs="#IMG.4" n="4"/>
        <p>Perhaps you have asked Dr <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2252">
Frederick Muller</persName> of the Hof-Bibliothek, Vienna.<note
            n="6" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2252">
Friedrich Müller</persName> (1854-1898), österr. Linguist u. Ethnograph; vgl. HSA 07571-07585. – Im Sinne von: „vielleicht haben Sie Dr. F. Müller schon befragt“?</note>
        </p>
        <p>I shall always be happy to serve you.</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Yours faithfully</salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1346">Robert Cust</persName>
          </signed>
          <dateline>Honorary Secretary<lb/> of Royal asiatic Society<lb/> London </dateline>
        </closer>
        <postscript>
          <p>You will find at N<hi rendition="#sup">o</hi> 196 of the enclosed book<note n="7" place="foot"
              type="editorial">Nicht beigefügt</note> a specimen of Negro-English of <placeName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.5865">
Surinam</placeName>.</p>
        </postscript>
      </div>
